column8: Laravel: Code Smart is a great introduction to Laravel.
column16: Ebooks, Ebook Child One, Ebook Child Three
column32: Laravel: Code Smart is a great introduction to Laravel, one of the most popular php frameworks. It is easy to read and understand, has great examples and shows you some of the best practices used in Laravel. The book is great for beginners and it teaches you how to set up a new project from scratch and build on it using the powerful features of the framework.

column8: PHP: The Right Way is a great tool for learning PHP.

It is translated in many different languages like English, German, Spanish, French and many more.

column3: Survive the Deep End: PHP Security
column8: This book helps to improve the security of your app.
column16: Ebooks, Ebook Child One, Ebook Child Three
column32: This book will show you how to improve the security of your app. It includes in-depth explanations of some of the most used security attacks, comprehensive examples and gives you advice on how to protect your application from them.

column8: The book covers the basics of PHP and is a handy resource.
column16: Ebooks, Ebook Child One, Ebook Child Three
column32: The book covers the basics of PHP and is a handy resource to keep around as a reference. It shows you how to use operators, structures, variables, functions, working with databases and much more, with great and easy to understand explanations, including a number of examples for each topic. Although it is written for PHP5, almost everything still applies for PHP7 thanks to the language's backwards compatibility.

column8: A book for beginners, explains basic properties of the language.

column8: Domain Driven Design is an approach to model complex software.

It is a great resource for intermediate and advanced developers.

column32: Tesla’s Elon Musk says that advances in Artificial Intelligence present a “fundamental risk to the existence of civilization.” Salesforce CEO Marc Benioff believes Facebook ought to be regulated like a tobacco company because social media has become (literally?) carcinogenic. And Russian zillionaire George Soros last week called Google “a menace to society.” Eschewing much of the over-the-top luddism that now fills the New York Times (“Silicon Valley is Not Your Friends”), the Guardian (“The Tech Insiders Who Fear a Smartphone Dystopia”), and other mainstream media outlets, Keen proffers practical solutions to a wide range of tech-related woes. These include persistent public and private surveillance, labor displacement, and fake news.
